{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:11:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:11:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14577"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14577"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.57,0.06,0.07,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115946"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7270"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97945"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3354"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33761"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49543"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115946"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three month history of worsening abdominal bloating, diarrhoea and unintentional weight loss of 4 kg. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, and partial small bowel resection for adhesive bowel obstruction five years ago. Her medications include metformin, pantoprazole, and insulin glargine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and mildly distended with generalised tenderness but no peritonism. Her body mass index is 19 kg/m2. Recent blood tests show an iron deficiency anaemia, with a haemoglobin of 10g/L (115-165) and ferritin 12 mcg/L (30-200). Vitamin B12 is 150 pmol/L (200-680), and folate is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Empiric rifaximin","Colonoscopy","Lactose breath test","Discontinue pantoprazole","Coeliac serology"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO), including chronic diarrhoea, bloating, and malabsorption (evidenced by weight loss and micronutrient deficiencies). She has multiple risk factors including diabetes (which can affect gut motility), previous bowel surgery (which can create anatomical changes promoting bacterial overgrowth), and proton pump inhibitor use (which reduces acid barrier). However, before this is assumed to be the correct diagnosis, other conditions should be considered. Of prime importance is to exclude a gastrointestinal tract malignancy. A carcinoma of the colon could explain her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be important to exclude malignancy in an elderly patient with iron deficiency anaemia, even if the clinical picture is more consistent with SIBO. A therapeutic trial of antibiotics would be reasonable, but this patient must have a colonoscopy as an initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpiric rifaximin\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as first-line therapy given the high clinical suspicion for SIBO and multiple predisposing factors - provided bowel malignancy has been excluded. Rifaximin is a non-absorbable antibiotic that is effective against intestinal bacteria and has shown good results in treating SIBO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac serology\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered, but the patient\u0027s age of onset and multiple risk factors for SIBO make this diagnosis less likely. Additionally, coeliac disease typically presents with more prominent malabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinuing pantoprazole\u003C/strong\u003E might help prevent recurrence of SIBO in the long term, but would not address the acute presentation. The patient\u0027s GORD symptoms would also need to be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactose breath test\u003C/strong\u003E can help diagnose SIBO but is not readily available in many centres and has poor sensitivity and specificity. When clinical suspicion is high, empiric therapy is reasonable without breath testing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO) commonly presents with bloating, diarrhoea and malabsorption symptoms.","Risk factors for SIBO include conditions affecting intestinal motility, anatomy, or acid suppression.","Empiric antibiotics are appropriate first-line therapy when SIBO is clinically suspected in a patient with predisposing factors.","A colonoscopy must be performed to exclude large bowel malignancy."],"references":["Zafar H, Jimenez B, Schneider A. Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth: current update. Curr Opin Gastroenterol 2023, 39:522\u201328."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97945"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97945"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T16:55:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T16:56:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7270"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115946"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":n